{"title_page": "Liang Wenbo", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese professional snooker player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = Liang Wenbo\n| image         = Liang Wenbo PHC 2016.jpg\n| caption       = Paul Hunter Classic 2016\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1987|3|05}}\n| birth_place   = [[Zhaodong]], [[Heilongjiang]], China\n| Sport country = {{CHN}}\n| Nickname      = The Fearless<ref name=\"timeslwkd\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3804732.ece|title=Ken Doherty loses status after fearless show from Liang Wenbo|accessdate=5 September 2008|publisher=The Times Online|author=Phil Yates | location=London | date=24 April 2008}}</ref><br/>The Firecracker<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/liang-claims-maiden-ranking-title/ |title=LIANG CLAIMS MAIDEN RANKING TITLE |accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n| Professional  = 2005\u2013\n| High ranking  = 11 {{Smaller|(October, December 2016 and May 2017)}}<ref>{{cite web|title=WORLD RANKINGS After 2016 International Championship|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111180729/http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 November 2016|website=World Snooker|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=WORLD RANKINGS After 2016 Betway UK Championship|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207072957/http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 December 2016|website=World Snooker|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517175634/http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 May 2017 |title=WORLD RANKINGS After 2017 Betfred World Championship|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref>\n| Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,041,528\n| High break    = '''[[Maximum break|147]]''': <small>(3 times)</small><ref name=\"worldsnooker.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa/official-147s/ |title=Official 147s \u2013 World Snooker |accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n| Century break = 255\n| Ranking wins  = 1\n| Minor wins    = 1\n| Other wins    = 1\n| World champ   =\n| medals-expand = yes\n| medals        = \n{{MedalCountry | {{CHN}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[snooker]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Cue sports at the 2013 World Games|2013 Cali]] | [[Snooker at the 2013 World Games \u2013 men's singles|Singles]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Cue sports at the 2006 Asian Games|2006 Doha]] | [[Cue sports at the 2006 Asian Games \u2013 Men's snooker singles|Singles]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2006 Doha | [[Cue sports at the 2006 Asian Games \u2013 Men's snooker team|Team]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games|2010 Guangzhou]] | [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games \u2013 Men's snooker team|Team]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Indoor Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Cue sports at the 2009 Asian Indoor Games|2009 Ho Chi Minh City]] | [[Cue sports at the 2009 Asian Indoor Games#Six-red snooker singles|Six-red singles]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Cue sports at the 2013 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games|2013 Incheon]] | Team }}\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| title = Liang Wenbo\n| c = \u6881\u6587\u535a\n| p = Li\u00e1ng W\u00e9nb\u00f3\n| w = Liang<sup>2</sup> W\u00ean<sup>2</sup>po<sup>2</sup>\n| mi = {{IPAc-cmn|l|iang|2|-|wen|2|b|o|2}}\n}}\n\n'''Liang Wenbo''' ({{zh|c=\u6881\u6587\u535a}}, [[pinyin]]: Li\u00e1ng W\u00e9nb\u00f3; born 5 March 1987) is a Chinese professional [[snooker]] player. He is left-handed. Liang is based at the Oracle Snooker Club, Abingdon [[Oxfordshire]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Amateur years===\nAs an amateur, Liang's major feats were as follows:<ref name=\"gcslw\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Players/Global_Asia/China/china_liang_wenbo.htm|title=Player Profile: Liang Wenbo|accessdate=5 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|year=2006|author=Janie Watkins|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208142302/http://globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Players/Global_Asia/China/china_liang_wenbo.htm|archive-date=8 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* 2003 [[IBSF World Snooker Championship]], men's division, quarter-finalist\n* 2004 IBSF World Snooker Championship, under-21 division, semi-finalist\n* 2005 [[International Open Series]], under-21 division, no. 4 runner-up\n\nLiang built on the positive start to his snooker career, winning an individual silver medal and a team gold medal at the [[Cue sports at the 2006 Asian Games|2006 Asian Games]].\n\n===2004/2005===\nLiang began his professional career during the [[2004\u201305 snooker season]] playing on the [[Challenge Tour (snooker)|Challenge Tour]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cuetracker.net/pages/players.php?ID=49&season=2004/2005 | title=Liang Wenbo - Season 2004/2005 | accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> which is the tier below the World Snooker Association Main Tour. He finished a mediocre 104th out of 168 competitors, having only accumulated 2150 points.<ref name=\"0405ct\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/04-5CTranks.htm |title=2004-5 Challenge Tour Rankings |accessdate=5 September 2008 |publisher=Global Snooker Centre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219151429/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/04-5CTranks.htm |archivedate=19 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===2005/2006===\nLiang received a wildcard nomination to the Main Tour despite not qualifying directly;<ref name=\"0506maintour\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/05-6mtlist.htm |title=2005-6 Main Tour List |accessdate=5 September 2008 |publisher=Global Snooker Centre |year=2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219151608/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/05-6mtlist.htm |archivedate=19 December 2008 }}</ref> this was because he won the 2005 [[IBSF World Snooker Championship|IBSF World Under-21 Championship]], and also because not all of the players that were eligible for the Main Tour took their places.<ref name=\"isdf-u21-2005\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.csns.ca/Archives/ibsfjsnk.html|title=IBSF UNDER-21 WORLD SNOOKER CHAMPIONSHIPS|accessdate=5 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706174005/http://www.csns.ca/Archives/ibsfjsnk.html|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In his first ranking tournament, the [[2005 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], he lost in the first qualifying round to [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] 2\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/2005GrandPrix.htm |title=2005 Grand Prix at the Global Snooker Centre |accessdate=5 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814222934/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/2005GrandPrix.htm |archivedate=14 August 2007}}</ref> He fared better in the next ranking event, the [[2005 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], where he almost whitewashed [[Alfred Burden]] in the first qualifying round 9\u20131, but subsequently lost in the second qualifying round to [[Marcus Campbell]] by the narrowest of margins, 8\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/05UK.htm |title=2005 UK Championship at the Global Snooker Centre |accessdate=5 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815153604/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/05UK.htm |archivedate=15 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nLiang qualified for his first ranking event at the [[2006 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], beating [[Sean Storey]], [[Jamie Burnett]] and [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] to reach the main draw. He defeated [[Nigel Bond]] in the first round 5\u20130, but his run was halted when he lost to [[Graeme Dott]] 3\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/05-6WelshOpen.htm |title=2006 Welsh Open at the Global Snooker Centre |accessdate=5 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070322185315/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/05-6WelshOpen.htm |archivedate=22 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2005 Malta Cup|Malta Cup]], however, he lost in the first qualifying round to [[Paul Davies (snooker player)|Paul Davies]] 3\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/05Malta.htm |title=2005 Malta Cup at the Global Snooker Centre |accessdate=5 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814221209/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/05Malta.htm |archivedate=14 August 2007}}</ref> At the [[2005 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], he beat [[David McDonnell]] and [[Matthew Couch]] before losing against [[Adrian Gunnell]] 3\u20135 in the third qualifying round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/05China.htm |title=2006 China Open at the Global Snooker Centre |accessdate=5 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818192354/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/res05_6/05China.htm |archivedate=18 August 2007}}</ref> He ended the season falling at the first hurdle at the [[2005 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], losing to [[Joe Delaney (snooker player)|Joe Delaney]] 5\u201310 in the first qualifying round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2005-6/06worldqual.htm |title=2006 World Championship at the Global Snooker Centre |accessdate=21 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703192042/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2005-6/06worldqual.htm |archivedate=3 July 2007}}</ref> Liang ended his debut season on the professional tour ranked 78th, a position that would not guarantee a place in the following season's tour; however, he had finished inside the top 8 of the one year ranking list, which qualified him for a place on the main tour for the next season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/06-7maintourlist.htm |title=2006-7 Main Tour \u2013 Eligible Players |access-date=6 September 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219151449/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/06-7maintourlist.htm |archive-date=19 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2006/2007===\nDuring the [[2006\u201307 snooker season|2006\u201307 season]], Liang reached at least the second round of qualifying in every ranking event. At the [[2006 Northern Ireland Trophy|Northern Ireland Trophy]], he beat [[Robert Stephen]] 5\u20130 before falling to [[David Gilbert (snooker player)|David Gilbert]] 0\u20135 in qualifying.<ref name=\"06nrt\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/06-NItrophy.htm|title=2006 Northern Ireland Trophy|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005051817/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/06-NItrophy.htm|archive-date=5 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, at the [[2006 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], Liang came top of his qualifying group, above more experienced players such as [[Gerard Greene]] and [[Barry Pinches]]. He finished fourth in his group at the round-robin stage, and although he did not progress to the next round, he did beat former world champion and world number one [[Stephen Hendry]] 3\u20130.<ref name=\"06GP\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/06-Grand%20Prix.htm|title=2006 Grand Prix|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821222346/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/06-Grand%20Prix.htm|archive-date=21 August 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the [[2006 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], he lost in the second round of qualifying to [[Jamie Burnett]] 7\u20139.<ref name=\"06UK\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/06_UK.htm|title=2006 UK Championship|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081224055315/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/06_UK.htm|archive-date=24 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the following ranking event, the [[2007 Malta Cup|Malta Cup]], he lost to [[Shailesh Jogia|Joe Jogia]] 3\u20135, again in the second round of qualifying.<ref name=\"0607malta\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/06-7Malta.htm|title=2006-7 Malta Cup|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205165017/http://globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/06-7Malta.htm|archive-date=5 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> He qualified for the [[2007 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], his third ranking tournament, by beating [[Dene O'Kane]], Joe Jogia and [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]]. He met Nigel Bond again in the last 48, this time losing only 3\u20135.<ref name=\"07welsh\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/2007-Welsh-Open.htm|title=2007 Welsh Open|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227042244/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/2007-Welsh-Open.htm|archive-date=27 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2007 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], he continued his run of reaching the second round of qualifying in every ranking tournament, and beat Robert Stephen before losing to [[Finland]]'s [[Robin Hull]].<ref name=\"07china\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/2007-China-Open.htm|title=2007 China Open|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715202659/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/2007-China-Open.htm|archive-date=15 July 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the [[2007 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], he beat [[Jeff Cundy]] before losing to [[Mike Dunn (snooker player)|Mike Dunn]].<ref name=\"07worlds\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/2007-888-qual1.htm|title=2007 World Snooker Championship|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819071719/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2006-7/2007-888-qual1.htm|archive-date=19 August 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> After a modest season, he improved on his tour ranking by finishing in 66th place, just outside the top 64;<ref name=\"0607rank\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/06-7prov-ranks.htm|title=2006-7 Main Tour \u2013 Final Rankings|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219151630/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/06-7prov-ranks.htm|archive-date=19 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> and he topped the one year ranking list to ensure his place on the WSA Tour for next season.<ref name=\"0607oneyrrank\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/06-7one-year-ranks.htm|title=2006-7 Main Tour \u2013 One Year Rankings|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219151624/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/06-7one-year-ranks.htm|archive-date=19 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2007/2008===\nLiang started the season by almost qualifying for the [[2007 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], however Nigel Bond beat him 5\u20133 in the last qualifying round, preventing him from appearing at his home tournament. At the [[2007 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], he could not repeat the success of last season and failed to qualify, finishing third on frame difference. He had more luck at the next tournament, the [[2007 Northern Ireland Trophy|Northern Ireland Trophy]], where he won through the qualifying rounds, beating [[Fraser Patrick]], [[Joe Delaney (snooker player)|Joe Delaney]] and [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] on the way. He faced Gerard Greene in the last 48, but lost 2\u20135. He had less success at the [[2007 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], losing in the second qualifying round to [[David Roe]] 2\u20139. He also failed to qualify for the [[2008 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], when he was dispatched in the last qualifying round by [[Andrew Norman]] 2\u20135. He fell at the first hurdle at his other home tournament, the [[2008 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], losing in the first qualifying round to [[Steve Mifsud]], who at the end of this season was ranked 54 places below Liang.<ref name=\"0708rank\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/2007-8-prov-ranks.htm |title=2007-8 Main Tour Rankings |accessdate=6 September 2008 |publisher=Global Snooker Centre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410222021/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/2007-8-prov-ranks.htm |archivedate=10 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2008 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], Liang was the third Chinese player to qualify for the main draw, defeating [[Ben Woollaston]], [[Rod Lawler]], [[David Gilbert (snooker player)|David Gilbert]] and [[Ian McCulloch (snooker player)|Ian McCulloch]] in the qualifying rounds. He met [[Ken Doherty]] in the first round of the championship, and defeated him 10\u20135. Before the start of this match, he accidentally entered the arena at the same time as the match officials and had to hurry back; he subsequently received a warm ovation when he entered the arena for a second time after being introduced by MC Rob Walker.<ref name=\"lw1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bso93-OwBI0|title=Liang Wenbo's Days in Crucible Theatre 2008|accessdate=6 September 2008}}</ref> For every session thereafter, Walker introduced him as \"[[Should I Stay or Should I Go|Should he stay or should he go]]... Liang Wenbo\", despite the rhyme occurring due to a mispronunciation of his name (\"bo\" is pronounced \"bwor\" in Chinese).\n\nLiang faced [[Northern Ireland]]'s [[Joe Swail]] in the last 16 of the tournament. In a humorous incident, Liang fluked a red after scattering the balls, but failed to notice and went back to his seat. To the amusement of the spectators, Swail pointed out the mistake and the referee called Liang back to the table.<ref name=\"lw1\" /> In the 23rd frame, with a 12\u201310 lead, Liang prematurely celebrated winning the match after potting \"match ball\", only to then lose the frame due to a snooker; Swail came back to level the match at 12\u201312. In the final frame, Liang made early breaks of 34 and 30. He missed the final yellow but snookered Swail, leaving the cue ball in the jaws of the pocket. Liang followed up with a safety shot but Swail snookered him behind the blue; Liang failed to hit the yellow ball so Swail had the white replaced. In his second attempt, Liang hit the yellow directly and went on to win the frame 74\u201334, and thus the match, 13\u201312.<ref name=\"lwjs\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/7370116.stm|title= Liang edges out Swail in classic|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=BBC Sport| date=28 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe incident in the last frame proved controversial as the referee replaced the cue ball in the wrong position, giving Liang a better sight of the yellow. At the time, Swail nodded his assent to the referee, but he complained in a post-match interview that Liang had behaved unprofessionally by not pointing out the referee's error. Commentators countered that Swail should have queried the placement of the ball before Liang took his shot, and that, given the tension of the situation, Liang could be forgiven for not thinking clearly.<ref name=\"lwjs\" />\n\nLiang faced eventual champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the quarter-final, taking the first two frames with a break of 80 in the first, but O'Sullivan had levelled the match 4\u20134 by the end of the first session. O'Sullivan eased ahead in the second session and eventually won the match 13\u20137. Liang's run to the quarter-finals of the World Championship gained him 5000 ranking points, boosting his final ranking to number 40 in the world.<ref name=\"0708rank\" /> This guaranteed that he would only have to win two qualifying matches to enter the main draw of the ranking tournaments the following season.\n\n===2008/2009===\nLiang began the new season by qualifying for the last 48 of the [[2008 Northern Ireland Trophy|Northern Ireland Trophy]]. He then beat [[Steve Davis]] and [[Peter Ebdon]] to reach the last 16, where he lost to [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] 1\u20135. This result lifted him to a provisional career high of 26 in the world.<ref name=\"prov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/provisional.htm|title=Provisional World Rankings|accessdate=6 September 2008|publisher=World Snooker}}</ref> He reached the main draw of the [[2008 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] by winning two qualifying matches, but then succumbed to [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the first round of the main draw. He then made a [[Maximum break|147]] and three other centuries (including two total clearances of 139) in a 5\u20131 victory over [[Martin Gould]] in the third qualifying round of the [[2008 Bahrain Championship|Bahrain Championship]]. However, he failed to qualify for the main draw, losing 2\u20135 to [[Michael Judge]].<ref>[http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-tournaments-bahrain-snooker-championship-08-09-qualifying-results.asp Global Snooker: Qualifying Results] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212223750/http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-tournaments-bahrain-snooker-championship-08-09-qualifying-results.asp |date=12 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFor the two Chinese events on this season's tour, Liang's two qualifying matches were held over until the venue stages. At the [[2008 Shanghai Masters]], he defeated [[Atthasit Mahitthi]] and [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] to reach the main draw, but lost to [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] 0\u20135 in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2008-9/Professional/2008-shanghai-draw.htm |title=2008 Shanghai Masters Trophy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080819224442/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2008-9/Professional/2008-shanghai-draw.htm |archivedate=19 August 2008 |accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref> Ironically, his second qualifying match for the Welsh Open was held over to ensure that his Welsh opponent [[Dominic Dale]] played at the main venue in Newport.\n\nLiang ended the season at the [[2009 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], after defeating [[Dave Harold]] 10\u20133 in the last qualifying round.<ref>[http://www.worldsnooker.com/ws_championship_qualifiers_second_news-24313.htm?tid=122 Twice-Champ Williams Secures Crucible Place] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430052554/http://www.worldsnooker.com/ws_championship_qualifiers_second_news-24313.htm?tid=122 |date=30 April 2009 }}</ref> He lost in the first round of the main draw 8\u201310 against [[Ding Junhui]].\n\n===2009/2010===\nIn July 2009, Liang won his first professional title, the [[2009 Beijing International Challenge|Beijing International Challenge]], beating world number 2 [[Stephen Maguire]] 7\u20136 in the final.<ref name=\"Wenbo Bags first Professional title in the BTV Beijing Challenge\">{{Cite web\n |url=http://www.global-snooker.com/Global-snooker-news-Wenbo-wins-in-china-120709.asp \n |title=Wenbo Bags first Professional title in the BTV Beijing Challenge \n |publisher=Global Snooker \n |date=12 July 2009 \n |accessdate=12 July 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717110031/http://www.global-snooker.com/Global-snooker-news-Wenbo-wins-in-china-120709.asp \n |archivedate=17 July 2009 \n}}</ref> He made a further breakthrough in August when he reached the final of the [[2009 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], becoming only the second [[China|Chinese]] player, and the fourth Asian man, to reach a ranking final. He ultimately finished runner-up to [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.worldsnooker.com/shanghai_masters09_news-70134.htm?tid=142\n| title = Liang Stuns Murphy To Reach Final\n| publisher = [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]\n| date = 12 September 2009\n| accessdate = 13 September 2009\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/8253375.stm|title=O'Sullivan seals Shanghai Masters |date=13 September 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nLiang qualified for the [[2009 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] but was defeated 2\u20135 by [[Peter Ebdon]] in the first round, winning the first two frames and losing the last five in succession. Prior to this meeting, he had played Ebdon twice, winning 5\u20131 and 5\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/6263054/Peter-Ebdon-beats-Liang-Wenbo-to-reach-Grand-Prix-second-round.html|title=Peter Ebdon beats Liang Wenbo to reach Grand Prix second round |date=5 October 2009|work=Telegraph|accessdate=7 October 2009 | location=London | first=Perry | last=Crooke}}</ref> He reached the quarter-finals of the [[2009 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] after defeating Ryan Day 9\u20133, and Mark King 9\u20132. He went on to lose 2\u20139 to John Higgins in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/UK_Championship_09_Draw.htm?tid=146 |title=2009 UK Championship |publisher=[[WPBSA]] |accessdate=17 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100416085926/http://www.worldsnooker.com/UK_Championship_09_Draw.htm?tid=146 |archivedate=16 April 2010 }}</ref> He failed to qualify for the [[2010 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] and the [[2010 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], as he lost 3\u20135 against [[Michael Judge]] and 2\u20135 against [[Andrew Higginson]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/welsh_open10_qualifying_draw.htm?tid=149 |title=2010 Welsh Open Qualifying |publisher=[[WPBSA]] |accessdate=18 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124074822/http://www.worldsnooker.com/welsh_open10_qualifying_draw.htm?tid=149 |archivedate=24 January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/china_open10_qualifying_draw.htm?tid=151 |title=2010 Sanyuan Foods China Open Qualifying |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |accessdate=4 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205080413/http://www.worldsnooker.com/china_open10_qualifying_draw.htm?tid=151 |archivedate= 5 February 2010 }}</ref>\n\nLiang qualified for the [[2010 World Snooker Championship|World Championships]] by defeating [[Rod Lawler]] 10\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/world_championship10_qualifying_draw.htm?tid=153 |title=2010 Betfred.com World Snooker Championship Qualifying |publisher=[[WPBSA]] |accessdate=17 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413104649/http://www.worldsnooker.com/world_championship10_qualifying_draw.htm?tid=153 |archivedate=13 April 2010 }}</ref> He was drawn against [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]], but lost 7\u201310.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/world_championship10_draw.htm?tid=154 |title=2010 Betfred.com World Snooker Championship |publisher=World Snooker |accessdate=4 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504141056/http://www.worldsnooker.com/world_championship10_draw.htm?tid=154 |archivedate= 4 May 2010 }}</ref> After the quarter-finals of the event, it was clear that Liang would be ranked as number 16 the [[2010\u201311 snooker season|following season]], the only new player entering the top 16 that season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rankings 2010/11 Season \u2013 Season Starting PositionsG|url=http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-snooker-rankings-09-10-provisional-ranking-list.asp|publisher=Global Snooker|accessdate=8 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017234705/http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-snooker-rankings-09-10-provisional-ranking-list.asp|archive-date=17 October 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2010/2011===\n\nLiang began the [[2010/2011 snooker season|season]] at the [[2010 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]], where he lost in the first round 2\u20135 against [[Marco Fu]].<ref name=\"WWW Snooker - 2010/2011\">{{cite web|title=Liang Wenbo \u2013 2010/2011|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=200|publisher=WWW Snooker|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> He participated at the [[2010 Beijing International Challenge|Beijing International Challenge]] to defend his first professional title, but lost in the semi-finals 4\u20136 against eventual winner [[Tian Pengfei]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BTV International 2010, 19\u201325 \u0438\u044e\u043b\u044f, \u041a\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0439|url=http://top-snooker.com/tournament/others/148|publisher=Top-Snooker.com|accessdate=8 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100926232824/http://www.top-snooker.com/tournament/others/148|archive-date=26 September 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Liang failed to qualify for the [[2010 World Open (snooker)|World Open]], as he lost 1\u20133 against [[Andrew Higginson]] and lost his first round match at the [[2010 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] 3\u20135 against [[Matthew Stevens]].<ref name=\"WWW Snooker - 2010/2011\"/> Having started the season inside the top 16, his results were not sufficient to maintain that position and he slipped out of the top 16.<ref name=cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk>{{cite web|last=Turner|first=Chris|title=Latest World Rankings|url=http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Rankings.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414214506/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Rankings.html|archivedate=14 April 2011|work=cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk|publisher=Chris Turner's Snooker Archive|accessdate=28 March 2011}}</ref> After this, he lost his qualifying matches in the five ranking tournaments.<ref name=\"WWW Snooker - 2010/2011\"/>\n\nLiang also participated at the [[Players Tour Championship 2010/2011|Players Tour Championship]], his best performance coming at the [[Euro Players Tour Championship 2010/2011 \u2013 Event 3|third European event]], where he reached the final, but lost 0\u20134 against [[Marcus Campbell]].<ref name=\"WWW Snooker - 2010/2011\"/> After 12 out of 12 events, he was ranked 14th in the Players Tour Championship Order of Merit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2010|title=Order of Merit|publisher=WWW Snooker|date=17 October 2010|accessdate=17 October 2010}}</ref> He lost his first round match at the [[Players Tour Championship 2010/2011 \u2013 Finals|Finals]] 1\u20134 against [[Ricky Walden]].<ref>{{cite web|title=PTC 2010/2011 Finals|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=32|publisher=WWW Snooker|accessdate=22 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2011/2012===\nLiang and [[Ding Junhui]] represented China at the [[2011 World Cup (snooker)|World Cup]] and they won in the final 4\u20132 against the [[Northern Ireland]] team.<ref>{{cite web|title=PTT-EGAT World Cup (2011) Results |url=http://www.pttegatsnookerworldcup.com/results |accessdate=11 July 2011 |work=pttegatsnookerworldcup.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801182613/http://www.pttegatsnookerworldcup.com/results |archivedate= 1 August 2012 }}</ref> During his match against [[Matthew Stevens]] in the first round of [[2011 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]], Liang had a chance to make his second [[maximum break]] in his career, but he snookered himself on the yellow ball, and the break ended at 120.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Selby / Liang misses out on maximum|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2397260,00.html|accessdate=20 July 2011|work=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Snooker]]}}</ref> He won the match 5\u20134 to reach the second round, where he lost 4\u20135 against [[Ken Doherty]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Goldfields Open (2011)|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=127|publisher=WWW Snooker|accessdate=21 June 2011}}</ref> He also qualified for the [[2011 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], but lost in the first round 1\u20135 against [[Neil Robertson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shanghai Masters (2011)|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=96|publisher=WWW Snooker|accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref> After this, he was unable to qualify for the next two ranking events, as he lost 2\u20136 against [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]] at the [[2011 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]],<ref>{{cite web|title=UK Championship Qualifiers (2011)|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=91|publisher=WWW Snooker|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref> and 3\u20135 against [[Liu Chuang (snooker player)|Liu Chuang]] at the [[2012 German Masters|German Masters]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 German Masters Qualifiers|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=92|publisher=WWW Snooker|accessdate=14 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, Liang joined Romford-based snooker Academy and management team Grove Leisure.<ref name=\"grove\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.grovesnooker.co.uk/2011/12/03/liang-wenbo-joins-the-grove/|title=Liang Wenbo joins the Grove|accessdate=3 December 2011|publisher=Grove Leisure|year=2011}}</ref>\nHe beat [[David Gilbert (snooker player)|David Gilbert]] and [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]], both 4\u20131, to reach the first round of the [[2012 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], where he faced [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] and was this time on the wrong end of a 4\u20131 scoreline.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2100657/Steve-Davis-beats-Ali-Carter-Welsh-Open.html | title=Davis back to his best to beat Carter and make last 16 at Welsh Open | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | date=13 February 2012 | accessdate=15 February 2012}}</ref> He narrowly missed out on a place in the [[2012 World Open (snooker)|World Open]] as he was defeated 4\u20135 by [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]] in the final round of qualifying.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/HainanWorldOpenQ/0,,13165~2577986,00.html |title=Results |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |accessdate=15 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304030822/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/HainanWorldOpenQ/0%2C%2C13165~2577986%2C00.html |archivedate= 4 March 2012 }}</ref> He also lost in qualifying for the [[2012 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] to the eventual winner of the event [[Peter Ebdon]] 0\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bank of Beijing China Open Qualifiers (2012)|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=94|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nLiang played in eleven of the twelve minor-ranking [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012|PTC]] events throughout the season, with a best finish in [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 10|Event 10]], where he lost in the quarter-finals to [[Dominic Dale]]. He also reached the last 16 in two other events to finish 38th in the PTC [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]], outside of the top 24 who qualified for the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Finals|Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2011|title=Order of Merit|publisher=WWW Snooker|date=8 January 2012|accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe qualified for the [[2012 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] by defeating [[Marcus Campbell]] 10\u20139. He had led the match 8\u20132 and 9\u20135 before Campbell took it to 9\u20139, at which point the match was suspended to allow players on the other tables to begin their sessions. Liang subsequently won the decider with a 72 break and played defending champion Higgins again in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2736795,00.html |title=Liang Survives Campbell Fight-Back |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]] |date=16 April 2012 |accessdate=25 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418222429/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2736795%2C00.html |archivedate=18 April 2012 }}</ref> He was involved in another final-frame decider, but was this time on the losing end as he bowed out of the tournament on the opening day, 9\u201310.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/17800380 | title=World Snooker Championship 2012: Higgins beats Liang | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | date=21 April 2012 | accessdate=25 April 2012}}</ref> He finished the season ranked world number 37.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |title=Official World Ranking List for the 2012/2013 Season |accessdate=16 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69tDLWozD?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0%2C%2C13165~176157%2C00.pdf |archivedate=13 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===2012/2013===\nLiang lost in qualifying for both the [[2012 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]] and the [[2012 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] to [[Rod Lawler]]. He reached the venue stage of the [[2012 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]] by beating [[Thanawat Thirapongpaiboon]], but lost 3\u20135 in the first round against [[Matthew Stevens]].<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{citation |title=Liang Wenbo 2012/2013 |publisher=Snooker.org <!--|accessdate=17 April 2013-->}}.</ref> Liang beat [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]] and [[Andrew Higginson]] to qualify for the [[2012 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], where he saw a 4\u20133 lead in the first round against [[Barry Hawkins]] turn into a 4\u20136 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/uk_snooker_championship/10083899.Barry_Hawkins_flies_through_to_second_round/ |title=Barry Hawkins flies through to second round of UK Snooker Championships |newspaper=[[The Press (York)|The Press]] |accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> Liang failed to qualify for the next two events, but won two matches to enter the main draw of both the [[2013 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] and the [[2013 China Open (snooker)|China Open]]. In Wales he lost 2\u20134 to local favourite Stevens in the first round, and in his homeland of China he beat Lu Ning 5\u20131 in the wildcard round, before losing 3\u20135 to [[Stuart Bingham]] in the first round.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> Liang had a very consistent season in the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013|Players Tour Championship]] series as he advanced to, but not past, the last 16 in five of the ten events.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> This saw him placed 27th on the PTC Order of Merit, one spot short of making the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Finals|Finals]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10 | title=Order of Merit 2012/2013 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> Liang's season ended when he was beaten 6\u201310 by [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]] in the final round of [[2013 World Snooker Championship#Qualifying|World Championship Qualifying]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=225 | title=Betfair World Championship Qualifiers | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> His end of year ranking was world number 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0,,13165~179273,00.pdf |title=Official World Snooker Ranking List For The 2013/2014 Season |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=28 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611202605/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0%2C%2C13165~179273%2C00.pdf |archivedate=11 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===2013/2014===\n[[File:Liang Wenbo at Snooker German Masters (Martin Rulsch) 2014-01-30 02.jpg|thumb|Liang Wenbo at the 2014 German Masters]]\nIn July 2013, Liang reached the final of the [[Snooker at the World Games 2013 \u2013 men's singles|World Games]] but lost in the gold medal match 0\u20133 to [[Aditya Mehta]].<ref name=\"2013/14\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=200&season=2013 | title=Liang Wenbo 2013/2014 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> He had an excellent season in the Asian Tour events by reaching the semi-finals of the [[Asian Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 2|Zhangjiagang Open]] where he was defeated 1\u20134 by [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]] and at the [[Asian Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 3|Zhengzhou Open]], where Liang won his first individual title on the World Snooker Tour.<ref name=\"2013/14\"/> He beat [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]] 4\u20133 in the semi-finals before whitewashing [[L\u00fc Haotian]] 4\u20130 to claim the \u00a310,000 first prize.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3508725,00.html | title=Wonderful Wenbo Wins In Zhengzhou | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> In the full ranking events, Liang won five successive frames against defending world champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the second round of the [[2013 International Championship|International Championship]] to triumph 6\u20134 which marked his first ever success over his opponent having lost in all four previous attempts.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/24733971 | title=Ronnie O'Sullivan loses to Liang Wenbo in International Championship | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> He then thrashed [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]] 6\u20131 to reach the quarter-finals of a ranking event for the first time in four years, where he lost 3\u20136 against [[Graeme Dott]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/24749569 | title=Peter Ebdon beats Neil Robertson at International Championship | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3518772,00.html | title=Ding Comes Through Ebdon Test | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> Liang reached the last 16 of both the [[2014 German Masters|German Masters]] and [[2014 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], losing 2\u20135 to [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]] and 2\u20134 to [[Barry Hawkins]] respectively.<ref name=\"2013/14\"/> A second final on the Asian Tour followed at the [[Asian Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 4|Dongguan Open]] where [[Stuart Bingham]] made four breaks above 50 to defeat him 4\u20131, but Liang still topped the [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014#Asian Tour|Order of Merit]] to qualify for the [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014 \u2013 Finals|Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Asian Order of Merit 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=26&season=2013|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> There, he was beaten 2\u20134 by [[Yu Delu]] and Liang was defeated 7\u201310 by [[Martin Gould]] in the final round of [[2014 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] qualifying.<ref name=\"2013/14\"/>\n\n===2014/2015===\nLiang overcame [[Jamie Burnett]] 5\u20131 in the first round of the [[2014 Wuxi Classic]], and then inflicted the first defeat on [[Mark Selby]] since he won the World Championship, beating him 5\u20133.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/28027795 | title=Wuxi Classic: Mark Selby loses to Liang Wenbo in China | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> In the last 16, Liang was knocked out 2\u20135 by [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/hull-of-a-performance/ | title=Hull of a Performance | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> He lost 3\u20135 against [[Robert Milkins]] in the opening round of the [[2014 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]], and in the wildcard round of the [[2014 Shanghai Masters (snooker)|Shanghai Masters]] 1\u20135 to Yan Bingtao.<ref name=\"2014/15\">{{cite web|title=Liang Wenbo 2014/2015|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2014&player=200|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> He failed to get past the last 64 of the next two ranking events, but won two matches to reach the [[2015 German Masters|German Masters]], where he eliminated [[Li Hang (snooker player)|Li Hang]] 5\u20131 in the first round. He reached the quarter-finals by coming back from 3\u20134 down against [[Stuart Bingham]] to win 5\u20134 on the final pink.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/osullivan-takes-route-66-past-perry/ | title=O'Sullivan Takes Route 66 Past Perry | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> He repeated this form when he edged [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] 5\u20134 to play in his second career ranking event semi-final,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/murphy-downs-rocket-in-thriller/ | title=Murphy Downs Rocket In Thriller | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> where he took four frames in a row to hold a narrow 4\u20133 advantage over [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]], before losing three successive frames in a 4\u20136 defeat.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/31209777 | title=German Masters: Shaun Murphy will play Mark Selby in final | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> Liang did not drop a single frame in seeing off [[Cao Xinlong]] and [[Gerard Greene]] at the [[2015 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], but was then the victim of a whitewash by [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] in the third round. At the inaugural [[2015 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], he lost 3\u20134 to [[Graeme Dott]] in the second round.<ref name=\"2014/15\"/> In the final round of [[2015 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] qualifying, he lost the last three frames against compatriot [[Zhang Anda]] to be narrowly defeated 9\u201310.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/sweet-16-through-to-sheffield/ |title=Sweet 16 Through to Sheffield |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=28 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422073001/http://www.worldsnooker.com/sweet-16-through-to-sheffield/ |archivedate=22 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===2015/2016===\nLiang was heavily beaten 2\u20138 by [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]] in the final of the [[2015 Six-red World Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/thepchaiya-reaches-a-nooh-level/ | title=Thepchaiya Reaches Nooh Level | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> In the third round of the [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], he took advantage of a collapse from [[Judd Trump]] to win 6\u20134 after trailing 1\u20134.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/34976937 | title=UK Championship: Judd Trump 'embarrassed' by collapse | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> He then saw off [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]] 6\u20135, after which Ford accused Liang of \"boring him off the table\" with slow play.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/35000646 | title=UK Championship: Tom Ford accuses Liang Wenbo of being boring | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> Liang responded by opening his quarter-final match against [[Marco Fu]] with three centuries and hung on to edge it 6\u20135, then came from 2\u20134 behind to reach the final by beating [[David Grace (snooker player)|David Grace]] 6\u20134.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.scmp.com/sport/article/1887002/chinas-liang-wenbo-holds-focus-repel-hong-kongs-marco-fu-ka-chun-snookers-uk | title=China\u2019s Liang Wenbo holds focus to repel Hong Kong\u2019s Marco Fu Ka-chun in snooker\u2019s UK Championship | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> It was the first final in the history of the event to feature two players from outside the United Kingdom; Liang lost the match 5\u201310 to eventual UK champion [[Neil Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/dec/06/neil-robertson-liang-wenbo-uk-championship | title=Neil Robertson overcomes Liang Wenbo to seal second UK Championship | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> A week later, he progressed to the semi-finals of the [[European Tour 2015/2016 \u2013 Event 5|Gibraltar Open]], but was whitewashed 0\u20134 by Fu.<ref name=\"2015/16\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=200&season=2015 | title=Liang Wenbo 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nLiang's UK final helped him break back into the top 16 in the world rankings to make his debut at the [[2016 Masters (snooker)|Masters]], where he was knocked out 4\u20136 by [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] in the opening round.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/35304084 | title=Masters 2016: John Higgins sees off Liang Wenbo | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> He was whitewashed 0\u20134 by [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] in the quarter-finals of the [[2016 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]].<ref name=\"2015/16\"/> After winning three matches to qualify for the [[2016 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], Liang lost 8\u201310 to [[Judd Trump]] after an earlier 7\u20133 lead.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/judd-trump-buys-drinks-fans-world-snooker/story-29157524-detail/story.html | title=Judd Trump buys drinks for his fans after World Snooker Championship first round fightback | newspaper=[[Bath Chronicle]] | accessdate=6 August 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== 2016/2017 ===\nIn the first round of the [[2016 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], Liang was narrowly beaten 4\u20135 by [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/37421959| title=Shanghai Masters: Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Liang Wenbo| publisher=[[BBC Sport]]| accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> He won five matches at the [[2016 English Open (snooker)|English Open]], which included a 4\u20133 second round victory over [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]], to reach the semi-finals.<ref name=\"2016/17\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=200&season=2016|title=Liang Wenbo 2016/2017| publisher=Snooker.org| accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> From 3\u20134 down, Liang made breaks of 134 and 138 and [[Stuart Bingham]] made a 116 to lock the score at 5\u20135. Liang took the decider and then ended [[Judd Trump|Judd Trump's]] 14-match winning streak in the final to win his maiden ranking title 9\u20136.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/liang-wins-classic-semi-final/| title=Liang Wins Classic Semi-final| publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]| accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> He became the second player from mainland China to win a ranking event and thanked O'Sullivan (with whom he practises daily) for his help.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/liang-claims-maiden-ranking-title/| title=Liang Claims Maiden Ranking Title| publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]| accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> The win also gave him entry to his first [[2016 Champion of Champions|Champion of Champions]] where he lost 0\u20134 in the opening round to [[Mark Selby]].<ref name=\"2016/17\"/>\n\nIn the [[2016 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]], Liang reached the quarter-finals, where he lost to [[Yu Delu]] 4\u20135.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/superb-fu-into-last-four/|title=Superb Fu into Last Four| publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]\n| accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> In the [[2017 Masters (snooker)|Masters]], he missed the final black, which would have seen him eliminate O'Sullivan 6\u20134 in the opening round of the [[2017 Masters (snooker)|Masters]], instead going on to lose 5\u20136.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/38630507|title=Masters 2017: Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Liang Wenbo in first-round thriller| publisher=[[BBC Sport]]| accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> A 4\u20130 thrashing of [[Dominic Dale]] and a pair of 4\u20133 victories over [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] and [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]] moved Liang into the semi-finals of the [[2017 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], where he was defeated 1\u20136 by [[Barry Hawkins]].<ref name=\"2016/17\" /> In the second round of the [[2017 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], Liang trailed [[Ding Junhui]] 2\u20136 after the first session and 7\u20139 after the second. He then won a trio of frames to take the lead in the match for the first time and would have been 12\u201311 ahead, one frame away from reaching the quarter-finals for the second time, but instead lost 12\u201313.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/ding-sets-osullivan-clash/|title=Ding Sets Up O'Sullivan Clash|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref> After the event, his end-of-season ranking rose to 11, which was a career-high.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rankings 2016/2017|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2016&template=31|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[2004\u201305 snooker season|2004/<br/>05]]\n! [[2005\u201306 snooker season|2005/<br/>06]]\n! [[2006\u201307 snooker season|2006/<br/>07]]\n! [[2007\u201308 snooker season|2007/<br/>08]]\n! [[2008\u201309 snooker season|2008/<br/>09]]\n! [[2009\u201310 snooker season|2009/<br/>10]]